---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../../components/PageHeader.astro';
import CtaSection from '../../components/CtaSection.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';

const lang = 'en';
const pathname = Astro.url.pathname;
---

<Layout title="About - Arcanesys" lang={lang} description="Independent EU practice. Authors of NixFleet and the nixfleet-compliance modules. Contributors to cloud-gouv/securix and nixpkgs.">
  <PageHeader
    lang={lang}
    pathname={pathname}
    titleKey="pageHeader.about.title"
    subtitleKey="pageHeader.about.subtitle"
  />

  <article class="prose max-w-prose mx-auto px-10 py-12">

    <h2><span class="num">01</span>What Arcanesys does</h2>
    <p>
      Arcanesys is an independent EU practice. We build NixFleet, declarative, signed
      GitOps for NixOS fleets with NIS2 / DORA / ISO 27001 / ANSSI BP-028 evidence
      produced as a side effect of operation. We work directly with operators who need
      their regulated zone migrated, audited, or extended under those regimes.
    </p>
    <p>
      Two engagement shapes are equally important to us. NixFleet ships as open source
      (MIT framework, AGPL control plane) — anyone can adopt it without ever speaking
      to us. Pilots, audits, and advisory are the way we go deep with a specific
      operator's regulated estate. <strong>No SaaS. No hosted control plane. Every
      deployment runs on the operator's own forge, cache, and infrastructure.</strong>
    </p>

    <h2><span class="num">02</span>What we have built</h2>
    <p>Three public repositories carry the work:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="https://github.com/arcanesys/nixfleet">arcanesys/nixfleet</a></strong> —
        framework, agent, control plane, CLI, CI. Around 44,500 lines of Rust across nine
        crates; 22 production Nix modules; mTLS, magic rollback with deadline, channel-gated
        waves, closure-hash quarantine. v0.2 tagged.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="https://github.com/arcanesys/nixfleet-compliance">arcanesys/nixfleet-compliance</a></strong> —
        16 typed compliance controls, 4 frameworks (NIS2, DORA, ISO 27001, ANSSI BP-028),
        JCS-signed evidence per host (RFC&nbsp;8785), governance engine with per-control
        exceptions and mandatory rationale.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="https://github.com/arcanesys/nixfleet-demo">arcanesys/nixfleet-demo</a></strong> —
        a four-VM reference fleet bootstrappable in about 10 minutes. Demonstrates the
        signed-artifact chain end to end on a single laptop.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The signed-artifact chain is exercised by 15 end-to-end fleet-harness scenarios.
      Evidence files are reproducible offline with <code>nixfleet-compliance-verify</code>:
      auditors do not have to trust us, the operator, or a scanner vendor — they verify the
      chain themselves with the three files the collector writes.
    </p>

    <h2><span class="num">03</span>Upstream work</h2>
    <p>Beyond our own repositories, we contribute to projects we depend on:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>cloud-gouv/securix</strong> — Sécurix is DINUM's hardened NixOS
        distribution. We have a flake-wrapper proposal in flight (issue&nbsp;#180, PR draft
        against&nbsp;#126) that lets downstream projects consume Sécurix as a flake input
        without enabling flakes per-host.
      </li>
      <li><strong>nixpkgs</strong> — packaging and module fixes upstreamed during the work on NixFleet.</li>
      <li>
        <strong>RFCs</strong> — twelve internal RFCs covering trust model, rollout lifecycle,
        hardware-rooted attestation, freshness windows, and air-gapped operation. Seven
        implemented, four at design stage with falsifiable done-criteria. All public in the
        nixfleet repo.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2><span class="num">04</span>The team</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Manuel Wegria</strong> — architecture, release engineering, the Rust agent
        and control plane. Authors most of the codebase.
        <a href="https://github.com/abstracts33d">github.com/abstracts33d</a>.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Vincent Romagnoli</strong> — pilots, compliance mapping, public-facing
        work. Handles operator-side conversations and regulatory anchoring.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      We work with a small set of EU NixOS contributors when a project benefits from it.
      Commercial engagements are delivered directly by the team.
    </p>

    <h2><span class="num">05</span>How we work</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>No SaaS.</strong> Every deployment runs on the operator's infrastructure. We hold no signing keys, no customer data, no telemetry.</li>
      <li><strong>MIT framework, AGPL control plane.</strong> The split is deliberate: integrators get permissive terms, hosters get viral terms. The compliance modules are MIT.</li>
      <li><strong>Hands-on.</strong> Pilots are paired engineering, not deck-and-handoff. Operator engineers leave able to run the fleet without us.</li>
      <li><strong>No NDAs to start.</strong> Public repositories, public RFCs, public mappings. Conversations get formal when a pilot agreement is signed.</li>
      <li><strong>EU-based.</strong> Invoicing from the EU, VAT applicable, no Cloud Act exposure on any part of the trust chain.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2><span class="num">06</span>Why now</h2>
    <p>
      NIS2 is transposed in France (Loi Résilience, March 2025) with full compliance
      required by end-2027. DORA has applied to financial entities since January 2025.
      ANSSI BP-028 v2.0 is the reference for French infrastructure hardening. SecNumCloud
      qualification and the EU Cyber Resilience Act are next on the horizon. These regimes
      need declarative tooling that produces signed evidence as a side effect of operation —
      not a separate compliance project layered on an imperative stack.
    </p>

    <h2><span class="num">07</span>Contact</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Pilot enquiries: <a href="mailto:contact@arcanesys.fr">contact@arcanesys.fr</a></li>
      <li>Security reports: <a href="mailto:security@arcanesys.fr">security@arcanesys.fr</a></li>
    </ul>

    <p class="text-center mt-10 flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-x-8 gap-y-3">
      <a href={`/${lang}/services/`} class="font-mono text-xs tracking-[1.5px] uppercase text-indigo hover:text-indigo-hover no-underline">
        See what we deliver →
      </a>
      <a href={`/${lang}/contact/`} class="font-mono text-xs tracking-[1.5px] uppercase text-indigo hover:text-indigo-hover no-underline">
        Open a conversation →
      </a>
    </p>
  </article>

  <CtaSection lang={lang} />
  <Footer lang={lang} />
</Layout>
